MU BMC meeting 2024

EM algorithm for bnc

Malcolm Hudson and Maurizio Manuguerra

11/11/2024

Goal

The purpose of this talk is to explore the effect of ill-conditioning of the likelihood on optimization in bnc linear models using maximum likelihood (ML) or maximum penalized likelihood (MPL).

bnc linear models

  • ML and MPL Estimation in Bivariate Linear Regression with conjugate Inverse Wishart prior for \(\Sigma\)
    • Following Andrs Ramrez-Hassan Ch. 4.4 (available online https://bookdown.org/aramir21/IntroductionBayesianEconometricsGuidedTour/multivariate-linear-regression-the-conjugate-normal-normalinverse-wishart-model.html#multivariate-linear-regression-the-conjugate-normal-normalinverse-wishart-model )
    • \(Y \sim \mbox{MVN}( XB, \Sigma \otimes I_N)\) where \(\Sigma\) is the variance-covariance of each \(i\)-th row of \(Y\), \(i=1,\ldots, N\). A prior distribution is then specified for \(B | \Sigma\) and for \(\Sigma\).

Particular case

The case with known means 0 and (unknown) variances 1; i.e.\(M=2,\, \beta_1= \beta_2= 0, \; \Sigma= \big(\begin{smallmatrix} 1 & \rho\\ \rho & 1 \end{smallmatrix}\big)\), in the absence of any covariates \(X\). Target estimation of the covariance matrix \(\Sigma\), or its inverse \(\Psi= \Sigma^{-1} = \big(\begin{smallmatrix} 1 & -\rho\\ -\rho & 1 \end{smallmatrix}\big) / \sqrt{1-\rho^2}.\)

  • Estimation of \(\Sigma\) or \(\Psi\) then takes as data the sum of squares and products (SSP) matrix \(V= \sum Y_i Y_i^{T}\) whose sampling distribution is Wishart on N=n d.f., with scale matrix \(\Sigma\).
  • Thus, with given means, the EMs M-step can estimate \(\hat{\Sigma}=V/n\) or \(\hat{\Psi}= n V^{-1}\).
  • MAP with a Wishart prior for \(\Psi\) with scale \(\Lambda^{-1}\) and \(\nu\) d.f. will instead use the posterior mode of \(\Psi\), given \(V\).
    • In this case the posterior is Wishart with scale \(V+\nu \Lambda^{-1}\) on \(n+\nu\) d.f. whose mode is \((n+\nu) (V+\nu \Lambda^{-1})^{-1}\).
  • Thus latent observations \(Y\) computed in the E-step provide complete data sufficient statistic \(V\) with Wishart distribution.

Optimization

For a maximum likelihood ML we provide optimizations MLtheta and MLEMtheta, with penalised equivalents PLtheta and PLEMtheta These were fitted used were package mle2 and the EM algorithms of package bnc.

Example with competing risks without censor time, from latent bivariate Normal

As an example test, we generated competing risks observations \((y^0,D)\), a sample of size \(n=10\), simulating from a bivariate Normal distribution with parameters \(\mu_1=\mu_2=1,\, \sigma_{11}=\sigma_{22}=1, \, \rho=0.25.\) The data on time to first event, \(y^0\), and the event cause, \(D\), is shown below; they form the first two columns of data frame datas1.0. In this case there is no censoring, so observed data in the EM algorithm is \(y_j^{obs} = (y_j^0, D_j)\) with \(D_j\) either 1 or 2.

EM algorithm (Gelman et al Ch.~18.3)

The EM algorithm for a single Normal sample (our case X=(1,,1)) is given as: \[ \mu_k^{new} = \sum y_{jk}^{old}/n , \] for \(k=1,2,\) \[ \sigma_{kl}^{new} = \sum (y_{jk}^{old} y_{jl}^{old}+c_{jkl}^{old})/n -\mu_k^{new} \mu_l^{new}, \] for \(k,l=1,2\), where \[\begin{align} y_{jk}^{old} &= \begin{cases} y_j^0 \; & \text{if } D_j=k \\ E(y_{jk}|y_j^0, D_j=k', \theta^{old}) & \text{if } D_j=k', k' \neq k \\ = E(y_{jk}|y_{jk} > y_j^0, \theta^{old}) \end{cases} \end{align}\] and \[\begin{align} c_{jkl}^{old} &= \begin{cases} 0 & \text{if } y_{jk} \text{ or } y_{jl} \text{ is observed} \\ cov(y_{jk},y_{jl}|y_j^0, D_j, \theta^{old}) & \text{if both } y_{jk}, y_{jl} \text{are unobserved} \end{cases} \end{align}\]

Application with bivariate competing risks

When \(D_j=1\) the first then the first definition provides \(y_{j1}^{old} = y_j^0\), while when \(D_j=2,\) it provides

\[\begin{align} y_{j1}^{old} &= E(y_{j1} \,|\, y_{j1} > y_j^0,\,y_{j2}=y_j^0,\, \theta^{old}) \\ &= E(z_{j1} \,|\, z_{j1} > a_j^0,\,z_{j2}=b_j^0,\,\rho) \\ &= E_{01}^{10}(a_j^0,b_j^0) \end{align}\]

where \(a_j^0 = \frac{y_j^0-\mu_{j1}^0}{\sigma_1^0};\; b_j^0 = \frac{y_j^0-\mu_{j2}^0}{\sigma_2^0}\).

When \(D_j=1\) then \(y_{j1}\) is observed, but not \(y_{j2}\); similarly, when \(D_j=2\) then \(y_{j2}\) is observed, but not \(y_{j1}\). In either case, whatever \(D_j \in \{1,2\}\), \(c_{j12}=c_{j21}=0\). Only when \(k=l\) will \(c_{jkk}=cov(y_{jk},y_{jk}|y_j^0, D_j, \theta^{old})\) when \(D_j \neq k\), otherwise it is \(0\). When \(D_j=2,\)

\[ c_{j11}=E[y_{j1}^2|y_{j1}>y_j^0, \, y_{j2}=y_j^0, \, \, \theta^{old}]-E[y_{j1}|y_{j1}>y_j^0, \, y_{j2}=y_j^0, \, \, \theta^{old}]^2 , \]

with a corresponding result for \(c_{j22}\) when \(D_j=1\). As \(y_{j1}=\mu_1^0 + z_{j1} \sigma_1^0\),

\[\begin{align} c_{j11} &= \text{var}[y_{j1}^2|y_{j1}>y_j^0, \, y_{j2}=y_j^0, \, \, \theta^{old}] \\ &= \sigma_{11}^0 \text{var}[ z_{j1}^2|z_{j1}>a_j^0, \, z_{j2}=b_j^0 ] \\ &= \sigma_{11}^0 \left\{ E_{01}^{20}(a_j^0, b_j^0) - \left[ E_{01}^{10}(a_j^0, b_j^0)\right]^2 \right\}, \end{align}\]

where \(a_j^0=(y_j^0-\mu_1^0)/\sigma_1^0, \; b_j^0=(y_j^0-\mu_2^0)/\sigma_2^0\). That is, after standardising variable \(y_1, y_2\) to standard normal marginals \(z_1, z_2\) using the current parameter estimate \(\theta=(\mu_1,\mu_2,\sigma_1,\sigma_2,\rho)\) we divide the dataset into two subgroups: z1[D==1], z2[D==1] and z1[D==2], z2[D==2], with z1 complete as observed in the first subgroup , but requiring imputation of z2, and with z2 complete as observed in the second subgroup , but requiring imputation of z1.

We can then utilise Lecture Notes on Missing Values of Julie Josse, available online_ml_inference_with_missing_values) , with \((z_1,z_2)\) a random sample of \(BVN(0,R)\) fixed means \(\mu_1=\mu_2=0\) to impute \(E[z_2|z_1, z_2>z_1 ]\) in the first data subset. Similarly, impute \(E[z_1|z_1>z_2, z_2]\) in the second.

Results

We summarise estimation using the BNC linear model applied to the competing risks example (n=10, no independent censoring) above. The true parameters are (1,1,1,1,0.25). ML estimates are obtained in R using two methods, mle2::mle2() and bnc:bnc() with PL=FALSE, parSigma=TRUE and objective function minuslogL().

The alternative parSigma=FALSE would use the EM algorithm for the natural parameter \(\Sigma^{-1}\), whose inverse would also provide the ML estimator, but these results are not shown here.
